Part I - U.S. Domestic Flights Data Exploration¶

by Leen Almudaifer¶

Introduction¶

The dataset under investigation is the T_ONTIME_REPORTING.csv, which contains flight-level records including departure and arrival times, delays, cancellations, diversions, and distances between airports. The aim of this exploration is to analyze patterns in flight delays, cancellations, and diversions, and to understand how these variables interact with factors such as departure hour, day of the week, and flight distance.

In [7]:
# Convert HHMM integer time to string HH:MM
def convert_to_time(val):
    if pd.isnull(val):
        return np.nan
    val = int(val)
    hh = val // 100
    mm = val % 100
    # Handle 2400 as 00:00
    if hh == 24 and mm == 0:
        hh = 0
    return f"{hh:02d}:{mm:02d}"
    


df['DEP_TIME'] = df['DEP_TIME'].apply(convert_to_time)
df['ARR_TIME'] = df['ARR_TIME'].apply(convert_to_time)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Number of rows and columns: (539,747, 11)

Key columns: FL_DATE, ORIGIN, DEST, DEP_TIME, DEP_DELAY, ARR_TIME, ARR_DELAY, CANCELLED, DIVERTED, DISTANCE

Data types: Mixed; dates were converted to datetime, times to HH:MM format, and delays separated into late and early arrivals.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

ARR_DELAY: arrival delay

CANCELLED: flight cancellation indicator

DIVERTED : flight diversion indicator

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

DEP_HOUR : departure hour

DAY_OF_WEEK : derived from FL_DATE

DISTANCE : flight distance

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of flights by day of the month is relatively uniform, with only slight fluctuations across days and a modest increase in activity at the beginning of January, likely related to postNew Year travel demand. No unusual outliers were observed in this distribution, and no transformations were required since the variable is already in an appropriate numeric format. For cancellations, the distribution is highly imbalanced: the vast majority of flights were not cancelled, with only a very small fraction showing cancellation. This result is consistent with expectations for commercial flight operations. No transformations were necessary, though the binary values were recoded (0 "No", 1 "Yes") for interpretability in plots.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Only adjustment made was to convert date and time fields (FL_DATE,DEP_TIME, ARR_TIME,) from string or HHMM formats into proper datetime values, ensuring consistency and enabling time-based analysis.

Bivariate Exploration¶

New columns for departure and arrival hours, as well as separate late and early arrival delays, were created to enable clear, time-based analysis of flight performance and to examine patterns in delays and diversions effectively.

In [11]:
# Function: Extract hour from time string
def extract_hour(df, col_name, new_col_name):

    df[new_col_name] = pd.to_datetime(df[col_name], format="%H:%M", errors='coerce').dt.hour
    return df

# Use the function
df = extract_hour(df, 'DEP_TIME', 'DEP_HOUR')
df = extract_hour(df, 'ARR_TIME', 'ARR_HOUR')
In [12]:
def split_delays(df, col_name):
    base = col_name.split('_')[0]
    df[f"{base}_Late"] = df[col_name].apply(lambda x: x if x > 0 else 0)
    df[f"{base}_Early"] = df[col_name].apply(lambda x: -x if x < 0 else 0)
    return df

df = split_delays(df, 'ARR_DELAY')

How does departure hour relate to late and early arrivals?

In [13]:
# Function: Reusable regplot with jitter
def regplot_with_jitter(df, x_col, y_col,scatter_color='#1f77b4', alpha=0.3, x_jitter=0.3, xlabel=None, ylabel=None, title=None):
    sns.regplot(
        data=df,
        x=x_col,
        y=y_col,
        x_jitter=x_jitter,
        scatter_kws={'alpha':alpha, 'color':scatter_color},
        fit_reg=False
    )
    if xlabel: plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    if ylabel: plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    if title: plt.title(title)
    plt.grid(True)

# Two-panel plot: DEP_HOUR vs Late/Early Arrival
plt.figure(figsize=(14,7))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
regplot_with_jitter(df, x_col='DEP_HOUR', y_col='ARR_Late',
                    xlabel='Departure Hour', ylabel='Arrival Delay (minutes)', title='Late Arrivals vs Departure Hour')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
regplot_with_jitter(df, x_col='DEP_HOUR', y_col='ARR_Early',
                    xlabel='Departure Hour', ylabel='Early Arrival (minutes)', title='Early Arrivals vs Departure Hour')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The analysis shows that late arrivals exhibit a noticeable trend across departure hours. Early arrivals are relatively rare, with a significant drop between hours 2 and 3, while higher frequencies of early arrivals are observed between hours 5 and 10.

Early vs. Late Arrivals by Day of Week?

In [15]:
# Extract day of week from flight date
df['DAY_OF_WEEK'] = pd.to_datetime(df['FL_DATE']).dt.day_name()

df['ARR_Status'] = df['ARR_DELAY'].apply(
    lambda x: 'Early' if x < 0 else ('Late' if x > 0 else np.nan)
)

# Group by day of week and arrival status
status_by_day = df.groupby(['DAY_OF_WEEK','ARR_Status']).size().reset_index(name='counts')

# Order days correctly
day_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']

# Plot
sns.barplot(
    x="DAY_OF_WEEK",
    y="counts",
    hue="ARR_Status",
    data=status_by_day,
    order=day_order
)

plt.xlabel("Day of Week")
plt.ylabel("Number of Flights")
plt.title("Early vs Late Arrivals by Day of Week")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Overall, we can also see that Thursdays have the highest number of flights, whereas Saturdays have the fewest, highlighting clear weekly operational patterns. Patterns of early and late arrivals reveal clear operational dynamics across the week. Early arrivals peak on Thursdays, with substantial volumes also on Wednesdays and Fridays, while Saturdays consistently see the lowest levels. In contrast, late arrivals are most concentrated on Fridays and Thursdays, with Tuesday standing out as the day least affected by delays.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Departure hour demonstrates a clear relationship with arrival delays: flights departing during early morning hours show a higher likelihood of being late, while peak daytime departures exhibit moderate late arrivals. Diversions are associated with certain departure times but remain relatively rare. Patterns of early and late arrivals also vary systematically by day of the week, reflecting operational or scheduling trends that influence punctuality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The day of the week has a notable impact on flight arrival status. Early arrivals are most frequent on Thursdays, followed by Wednesdays and Fridays, whereas Saturdays experience the fewest. Late arrivals peak on Fridays and Thursdays, with Tuesdays showing the least delays. Longer flights are generally more prone to lateness, and analyzing early versus late arrivals together highlights operational patterns not evident when examining delays in isolation. Splitting the ARR_DELAY column into ArrDelay_Late and ArrDelay_Early allowed for a more precise understanding of these temporal dynamics.

Multivariate Exploration¶

what are the average late arrival by Departure Time and day of week?

In [16]:
# Aggregate data: average Early and Late by DEP_HOUR and DAY_OF_WEEK
agg = df.groupby(['DAY_OF_WEEK','DEP_HOUR'])[['ARR_Late','ARR_Early']].mean().reset_index()

# Melt into long format for hue
agg_melt = agg.melt(id_vars=['DAY_OF_WEEK','DEP_HOUR'],
                    value_vars=['ARR_Late','ARR_Early'],
                    var_name='ARR_Stat', value_name='Average_Delay')

# Rename for readability
agg_melt['ARR_Stat'] = agg_melt['ARR_Stat'].replace({'ARR_Late':'Late', 'ARR_Early':'Early'})

# Ensure days are ordered
day_order = ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']
agg_melt['DAY_OF_WEEK'] = pd.Categorical(agg_melt['DAY_OF_WEEK'], categories=day_order, ordered=True)

# FacetGrid with hue
g = sns.FacetGrid(agg_melt, col='DAY_OF_WEEK', col_wrap=4, height=4, hue='ARR_Stat', sharey=False)
g.map_dataframe(sns.lineplot, x='DEP_HOUR', y='Average_Delay', marker='o')
g.set_axis_labels("Departure Hour", "Average Delay (minutes)")
g.set_titles(col_template="{col_name}")
g.add_legend(title="Arrival Status")
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
g.fig.suptitle("Average Early and Late Arrival Delay by Departure Hour and Day of Week")
plt.show()

Late arrivals show a clear concentration in the early morning, particularly before 5 AM, suggesting that overnight and pre-dawn operations face higher disruption risks. After 5 AM, delays begin to rise gradually across the day, likely reflecting accumulated scheduling pressures and traffic congestion.

In contrast, early arrivals are relatively less common before 4 AM, but they peak between 4 and 5 AM, indicating that flights departing in the early morning window are more likely to benefit from lighter traffic and favorable conditions that enable them to arrive ahead of schedule.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Across the multivariate analyses, several features jointly influenced flight performance. Departure hour, flight distance, and day of the week consistently affected arrival delays. Early-morning departures (before 4 AM) tend to be late, and longer flights show a higher likelihood of delays compared to shorter flights. The combination of departure hour and day of the week strengthened patterns observed in average late arrivals, showing that operational scheduling and day-specific trends amplify the effect of departure times. These interactions highlight that delays are not solely a function of a single variable but result from the interplay of multiple factors.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Short flights under ~3,000 miles are mostly on time, while longer flights are more likely to be delayed, especially when departing early. Although cancellations are rare, their patterns by day of the week align with late arrivals, suggesting operational constraints affect both. These interactions highlight the value of examining multiple features together to understand flight performance.

Conclusions¶

The exploration of the T_ONTIME_REPORTING dataset revealed patterns in flight delays, cancellations, and diversions, and how these relate to departure time, day of the week, and flight distance. Early and late arrivals, departure hours, and flight distance showed clear relationships with punctuality, while cancellations and diversions, though rare, highlighted operational trends. Multivariate analyses emphasized that multiple factors interact to influence flight performance, showing that considering features together provides a clearer understanding of delays and operational patterns. Overall, the analysis provides insight into how temporal and operational factors impact airline performance.
